                <div class="col-md-9">
                    <h5 style="font-weight:bold">Session 3| Measuring Informal Economy in Guatemala</h5>
                    <p>The informal economy is a crucial economic driver in the regions, with digitalization transforming it by leaps and bounds. Leveraging the technological underpinnings 
                        (big data generated) of this transformation to measure e-commerce activities in the informal economy, is of great importance to the regions.
                    </p>
                    <ul class="list-unstyled">                                                         
                        <li><strong>Presentation:</strong> <a href="~/groups/NetEconStat/Meetings/NetworkFourthMeeting/Session3-Informal-Sector-Guatemala.pdf" target= "_blank" style="color:blue">Measurement of the informal sector</a></li>
                        <li><b>Presenter:</b><i> Stefani Mar&iacute;a Villeda Guerra, Economic Analyst, Department of Macroeconomic Statistics, Bank of Guatemala</i></li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><b>Discussion (15 minutes)</b></p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <br>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-3">
                    <h5 class="events-time"><i class="fa fa-clock-o" style = "font-size:18px;color:red"></i> 7:45 am - 8:20 am </h5>
                </div>
                
                <div class="col-md-9">
                    <h5 style="font-weight:bold">Session 4| Overview of Outcomes of the Beyond GDP Sprint 2023 and Proposed Next Steps </h5>
                    <p>This session will run through the key issues which emerged from the Beyond GDP Sprint 2023, and outline the Network's recommendations, including the 
                        formation of a multi-disciplinary group comprising of experts from the social and demographic statistics, national accounts, environmental-economic 
                        accounting, environment statistics and geospatial communities, academia and, where appropriate, the private sector, to explore how to take forward 
                        the recommendations.
                    </p>
                        <ul class="list-unstyled">
                            <li><strong>Presentation:</strong> <a href="~/groups/NetEconStat/Meetings/NetworkFourthMeeting/Session4-Progress-of-the-Network-of-Economic-Statisticians-on-Beyond-GDP-Heys.pdf" target= "_blank" style="color:blue">Progress of the Network of Economic Statisticians on Beyond GDP</a></li>
                            <li><strong>Presenter:</strong> <i>Richard Heys, UK ONS and Ivo Havinga, Consultant</i></li>
                        </ul>
                    <p><b>Discussion (15 minutes)</b></p>              
                </div>
            </div>   
            
            <br>

            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-3">
                    <h5 class="events-time"><i class="fa fa-clock-o" style = "font-size:18px;color:red"></i> 8:20 am - 8:55 am </h5>
                </div>
                
                <div class="col-md-9">
                    <h5 style="font-weight:bold">Session 5| Discussion on proposed topics for further work by the Network  </h5>
                    <p>This session will provide participants with an opportunity to provide comments on two proposals of work that the Network would like to pursue in the coming year. Mr. Hadi Susanto will briefly 
                        speak about the idea of exploring, in collaboration with the Data Science Leaders Network, the potential of employing AI in statistical work. Mr. Andr&eacute; Loranger will put forth the proposal 
                        to organize some events that will allow national statistical offices to share their ideas on successful data strategies. This idea has emerged from a recent Network Informal meeting where 
                        participants showed interest in learning more about each other's experience in this area. 
                    </p>
                    <p>These short introductions of the proposals will be followed by a fulsome discussion with Network members, to seek their comments and suggestions on whether the Network should pursue the work 
                        and if so, in what way.
                    </p>
